Performing some Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to gather some relevant information for building the prediction model

First, looking into the distribution of the two target variables being H1N1 and Seasonal Vaccines

In [8]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, sharex=True)
n_obs = l_train.shape[0]
(l_train['h1n1_vaccine']
    .value_counts()
    .div(n_obs)
    .plot.barh(title="Proportion of H1N1 Vaccine", ax=ax[0])
)
ax[0].set_ylabel("h1n1_vaccine")
(l_train['seasonal_vaccine']
    .value_counts()
    .div(n_obs)
    .plot.barh(title="Proportion of Seasonal Vaccine", ax=ax[1])
)
ax[1].set_ylabel("seasonal_vaccine")
plt.show()

It looks like roughy half of people received the seasonal flu vaccine, but only about 20% of people received the H1N1 flu vaccine. In terms of class balance, we say that the seasonal flu vaccine target has balanced classes, but the H1N1 flu vaccine target has moderately imbalanced classes.

In [10]:
# Phi Coefficient
(l_train["h1n1_vaccine"]
    .corr(l_train["seasonal_vaccine"], method="pearson")
)
Out[10]:
0.37714265306144684

Having a phi coefficient of 0.37 indicates a moderate positive correlation, meaning that most people who got an H1N1 flu vaccine also got the seasonal flu vaccine; while a minority of people who got the seasonal vaccine got the H1N1 vaccine, got H1N1 vaccine at a higher rate than those who did not get the seasonal vaccine.

In [20]:
def vaccination_rate_plot(col, target, data, ax=None):
    counts = (j_train_back[[target, col]]
                  .groupby([target, col])
                  .size()
                  .unstack(target)
             )
    group_counts = counts.sum(axis='columns')
    props = counts.div(group_counts, axis='index')

    props.plot(kind="barh", stacked=True, ax=ax)
    ax.invert_yaxis()
    ax.legend().remove()

Now Building the model

In [22]:
# Importing the libraries
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

from sklearn.ensemble import VotingClassifier

from sklearn.multioutput import MultiOutputClassifier

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

Save all numerical columns into a single variable

In [23]:
numeric_cols = f_train.columns[f_train.dtypes != "object"].values

Now calling the classifiers used for the prediction model. We will develop a multi output classifier that will include 3 different models to evaluate performance at best

In [24]:
model_1 = LogisticRegression()
model_2 = XGBClassifier()
model_3 = RandomForestClassifier()

Now creating the pipeline. It is much easier to work with machine learning when using a pipeline. In this case, the pipelinne will use ColumnTransformer() to transform the columns and the estimators will be 3 in total using MultiOutputClassifier

In [25]:
numeric_preprocessing_steps = Pipeline([
    ('standard_scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('simple_imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median'))
])

# this will be the column transformer
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers = [
        ("numeric", numeric_preprocessing_steps, numeric_cols)
    ],
    remainder = "drop"
)


# these are the 3 model classifiers included as estimators
estimators = MultiOutputClassifier(
    VotingClassifier(estimators=[('lr', model_1), ('xgb', model_2), ('rf', model_3)], voting ='soft')
)


# this is the final pipeline
full_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ("preprocessor", preprocessor),
    ("estimators", estimators),
])

Now training the multi-output classifier and make a prediction

In [26]:
X_train, X_eval, y_train, y_eval = train_test_split(
                                                    f_train,
                                                    l_train,
                                                    test_size=0.33,
                                                    shuffle=True,
                                                    stratify=l_train,
                                                    random_state=101
                                                    )
